\begin_layout Section
Rules of thumb 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are not hard rules by no means! Do the analysis first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
The 1% (or 2%) rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Monthly rent divided by the value of the property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is a quick view about whether a property will produce a positive cash-flow.
 Higher is better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The best is above 2%.
 Below 1% won't probably produce a positive cash flow.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
The 50% rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How much cash flow to expect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On average and over time, half of the income of the property is spent on
 operating expenses.
 Taxes, insurance, utilities, repairs, vacancy, others.
 But this doesn't include mortgage payments.
 But some properties will require a tenant to pay for the utilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
The 70% rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For those who like to flip houses, this helps to determine how much to pay
 for a property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The most you should pay for the property should be 70% of the actual pair
 value.
 Minus repairs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So property with value $300k (its selling price) x 70% = $210k, minus $50k
 for repairs = $160k.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So you shouldn't pay more than $160k.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
30% should include holding costs, closing costs, and some profit an investor
 wants to make.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
The 5% rule 
\series default
(
