\begin_layout Itemize
It's about taking into account unrecoverable costs.
 However, this rule is just an oversimplification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
1%
\series default
 - Property taxes - generally it's 1% of the value of the home
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
1%
\series default
 - Maintenance costs - 1% of the property value per year on average
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
3%
\series default
 - Cost of capital - this has to be broken down into 2 pieces:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Cost of debt - mortgage interest, it can be usually around 3%
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cost of equity - you put usually 10-20% down and you made a choice to invest
 in a real estate asset.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Alternatively, you could continue renting and invest the down-payment.
 So this is an opportunity cost.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Return from real estate from 1900-2017 was 3% (or 1.3% in nominal terms),
 while stocks returned 6.9% (or 5.2% in nominal terms).
 So the expected return difference between real estate and stocks is 3.9%.
 So to keep things simple and to be a bit conservative, let's round that
 down to 3%.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Take the value of the home that you are considering, multiply by 5%, and
 divide by 12.
 If you can rent for less than that, then renting is better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It works the other way around too.
 Multiply your rent by 12 and divide by 5%.
 So if your rent is $1,000, then paying $1,000 in rent is financially equivalent
 in terms of unrecoverable costs to owning $240,000 house.
\end_layout

